[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:unity-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:unity-engine/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] ECS prioritizes composition over inheritance.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Every entity is defined not by a type hierarchy, but by the components associated with it.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Systems act globally over all entities that have the required components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a food system might iterate through every entity with a relevant component tracking hunger, and act on them to push them a little away from satiation at time intervals.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Entities lacking the component like terrain or items would be naturally ignored by the food system.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Due to an ambiguity in the English language, an interpretation of the name is that an ECS is a system comprising entities and components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In the 2002 talk at GDC, Scott Bilas compared a C++ object system and his new custom component system.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] This is consistent with a traditional use of *system* terms in general systems engineering with Common Lisp Object System and type system as examples.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Although mostly found in video game development, the ECS can be useful in other domains, such as in robotics simulators like Gazebo.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] ECS combines orthogonal, well-established ideas in general computer science and programming language theory.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, components can be seen as a mixin idiom in various programming languages.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Components are a specialized case under the general delegation approach and meta-object protocol.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] That is, any complete component object system can be expressed with the *templates* and *empathy* model within The Orlando Treaty vision of object-oriented programming.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] An entity represents a general-purpose object.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In a game engine context, for example, every coarse game object is represented as an entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Usually, it only consists of a unique ID.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] as possessing a particular aspect, and (the component) holds the data needed to model that aspect.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, every game object that can take damage might have a Health component associated with its entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] A system is a process that acts on all entities with the desired components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a physics system may query for entities having mass, velocity and position components, iterate over the results, and do physics calculations for each entity using the set of components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The behavior of an entity can be changed at runtime by systems that add, remove or modify components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] This eliminates the ambiguity problems of deep and wide inheritance hierarchies often found in object-oriented programming techniques that are difficult to understand, maintain, and extend.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Common ECS approaches are highly compatible with, and are often combined with, data-oriented design techniques.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Data for all instances of a component are contiguously stored together in physical memory, enabling efficient memory access for systems that operate over many entities.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In 1963, Ivan Sutherland's Sketchpad stored the visual elements of a drawing using an early form of an ECS.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Instead of encapsulating points in different objects (e.g. lines, circles, rectangles) points were stored in a ring buffer, and visual elements were only referencing them.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] When moving a point, this allowed updating all the shapes and constraints using it.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In 1998, *Thief: The Dark Project* pioneered an ECS.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The engine was later used for its sequel, as well as *System Shock 2*.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In 2002, Scott Bilas of Gas Powered Games (Dungeon Siege) gave a seminal talk on ECS.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] This inspired numerous later well-known implementations.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In early January 2007, Mick West who worked on the Tony Hawk series, shared his experiences on the process of ECS adoption at Neversoft.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Also in 2007, the team working on *Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising* experimented with ECS designs, including those inspired by Bilas/*Dungeon Siege*, and Adam Martin later wrote a detailed account of ECS design, including definitions of core terminology and concepts.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In particular, Martin's work popularized the ideas of systems as a first-class element, entities as identifiers, components as raw data, and code stored in systems, not in components or entities.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In 2015, Apple Inc. introduced GameplayKit, an API framework for iOS, macOS and tvOS game development that includes an implementation of ECS.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In October 2018 the company Unity released its megacity demo that utilized a tech stack built on an ECS.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Unity's ECS runs on a powerful optimized architecture known as DOTS, which "empowers creators to scale processing in a highly performant manner".
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The data layout of different ECS's can differ as well as the definition of components, how they relate to entities, and how systems access entities' components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Adam Martin defines in his blog series what he considers an Entity–Component–System.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] An entity only consists of an ID for accessing components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] It is a common practice to use a unique ID for each entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Some of these advantages can also be achieved using smart pointers.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Components have no game code (behavior) inside of them.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The components don't have to be located physically together with the entity, but should be easy to find and access using the entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Unity's layout has tables, each with columns of components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] In this system an entity *type* is based on the components it holds.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For every entity *type* there is a table (called an *archetype*) holding columns of components that match the components used in the entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] To access a particular entity one must find the correct archetype (table) and index into each column to get each corresponding component for that entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The normal way to transmit data between systems is to store the data in components, and then have each system access the component sequentially.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, the position of an object can be updated regularly.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] This position is then used by other systems.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] If there are a lot of different infrequent events, a lot of flags will be needed in one or more components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Systems will then have to monitor these flags every iteration, which can become inefficient.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] A solution could be to use the observer pattern.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] All systems that depend on an event subscribe to it.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The action from the event will thus only be executed once, when it happens, and no polling is needed.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The ECS has no trouble with dependency problems commonly found in object-oriented programming since components are simple data buckets and have no dependencies.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Each system will typically query the set of components an entity must have for the system to operate on it.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a render system might register the model, transformations, and drawable components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] When it runs, the system will perform its logic on any entity that has all of those components.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Other entities are simply skipped, with no need for complex dependency trees.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] However, this can be a place for bugs to hide, since propagating values from one system to another through components may be hard to debug.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] ECS may be used where uncoupled data needs to be bound to a given lifetime.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The ECS uses composition, rather than inheritance trees.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] An entity will be typically made up of an ID and a list of components that are attached to it.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] Any game object can be created by adding the correct components to an entity.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] This allows the developer to easily add features to an entity, without any dependency issues.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] For example, a player entity could have a *bullet* component added to it, which would then meet the requirements to be manipulated by some *bulletHandler* system, which then could result in that bullet doing damage to other objects by running into them.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] The merits of using ECS for storing the game state have been proclaimed by many game developers like Adam Martin.
[src:unity-engine/entity-component-system] One good example is the blog posts by Richard Lord, where he discusses the merits and why ECS-designed game data storage systems are so useful.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:unity-engine/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:unity-engine/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A **scene graph** is a hierarchical data structure commonly used by vector-based graphics editing applications and modern computer games, which cascades the inheritance or spatial representation of a set of objects.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] It is a collection of nodes in a graph or tree structure.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A tree node may have many children but only a single parent, with the effect of a parent applied to all its child nodes; an operation performed on a group automatically propagates its effect to all of its members.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In many programs, associating a geometrical transformation matrix (see also transformation and matrix) at each group level and concatenating such matrices together is an efficient and natural way to process such operations.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A common feature, for instance, is the ability to group related shapes and objects into a compound object that can then be manipulated as easily as a single object.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In vector-based graphics editing, each leaf node in a scene graph represents some atomic unit of the document, usually a shape such as an ellipse or Bezier path.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Although shapes themselves (particularly paths) can be decomposed further into nodes such as spline nodes, it is practical to think of the scene graph as composed of shapes rather than going to a lower level of representation.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Another useful and user-driven node concept is the layer.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A layer acts like a transparent sheet upon which any number of shapes and shape groups can be placed.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The document then becomes a set of layers, any of which can be conveniently made invisible, dimmed, or locked (made read-only).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Some applications place all layers in a linear list, while others support layers within layers to any desired depth.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Internally, there may be no real structural difference between layers and groups at all, since they are both just nodes of a scene graph.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] If differences are needed, a common type declaration in C++ would be to make a generic node class, and then derive layers and groups as subclasses.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A visibility member, for example, would be a feature of a layer, but not necessarily of a group.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Scene graphs are useful for modern games using 3D graphics and increasingly large worlds or levels.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In such applications, nodes in a scene graph (generally) represent entities or objects in the scene.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For instance, a game might define a logical relationship between a knight and a horse so that the knight is considered an extension to the horse.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The scene graph would have a 'horse' node with a 'knight' node attached to it.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The scene graph may also describe the spatial, as well as the logical, relationship of the various entities: the knight moves through 3D space as the horse moves.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In these large applications, memory requirements are major considerations when designing a scene graph.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For this reason, many large scene graph systems use geometry instancing to reduce memory costs and increase speed.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In our example above, each knight is a separate scene node, but the graphical representation of the knight (made up of a 3D mesh, textures, materials and shaders) is instanced.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This means that only a single copy of the data is kept, which is then referenced by any 'knight' nodes in the scene graph.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This allows a reduced memory budget and increased speed, since when a new knight node is created, the appearance data need not be duplicated.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The simplest form of scene graph uses an array or linked list data structure, and displaying its shapes is simply a matter of linearly iterating the nodes one by one.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Other common operations, such as checking to see which shape intersects the mouse pointer are also done via linear searches.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For small scene graphs, this tends to suffice.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Applying an operation on a scene graph requires some way of dispatching an operation based on a node's type.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For example, in a render operation, a transformation group node would accumulate its transformation by matrix multiplication, vector displacement, quaternions or Euler angles.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] After which a leaf node sends the object off for rendering to the renderer.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Some implementations might render the object directly, which invokes the underlying rendering API, such as DirectX or OpenGL.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] But since the underlying implementation of the rendering API usually lacks portability, one might separate the scene graph and rendering systems instead.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In order to accomplish this type of dispatching, several different approaches can be taken.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In object-oriented languages such as C++, this can easily be achieved by virtual functions, where each represents an operation that can be performed on a node.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Virtual functions are simple to write, but it is usually impossible to add new operations to nodes without access to the source code.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Alternatively, the *visitor pattern* can be used.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This has a similar disadvantage in that it is similarly difficult to add new node types.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Other techniques involve the use of RTTI (Run-Time Type Information).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The operation can be realised as a class that is passed to the current node; it then queries the node's type using RTTI and looks up the correct operation in an array of callbacks or functors.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This requires that the map of types to callbacks or functors be initialized at runtime, but offers more flexibility, speed and extensibility.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Variations on these techniques exist, and new methods can offer added benefits.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] One alternative is scene graph rebuilding, where the scene graph is rebuilt for each of the operations performed.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This, however, can be very slow, but produces a highly optimised scene graph.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] It demonstrates that a good scene graph implementation depends heavily on the application in which it is used.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Traversals are the key to the power of applying operations to scene graphs.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] At this point, many scene graph engines then traverse back up the tree, applying a similar operation.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For example, consider a render operation that takes transformations into account: while recursively traversing down the scene graph hierarchy, a pre-render operation is called.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] If the node is a transformation node, it adds its own transformation to the current transformation matrix.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Once the operation finishes traversing all the children of a node, it calls the node's post-render operation so that the transformation node can undo the transformation.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This approach drastically reduces the necessary amount of matrix multiplication.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Some scene graph operations are actually more efficient when nodes are traversed in a different order – this is where some systems implement scene graph rebuilding to reorder the scene graph into an easier-to-parse format or tree.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] For example, in 2D cases, scene graphs typically render themselves by starting at the tree's root node and then recursively draw the child nodes.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The tree's leaves represent the most foreground objects.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Since drawing proceeds from back to front with closer objects simply overwriting farther ones, the process is known as employing the Painter's algorithm.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In 3D systems, which often employ depth buffers, it is more efficient to draw the closest objects first, since farther objects often need only be depth-tested instead of actually rendered, because they are occluded by nearer objects.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVHs) are useful for numerous tasks – including efficient culling and speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A BVH is a spatial structure, but doesn't have to partition the geometry (see spatial partitioning below).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A BVH is a tree of bounding volumes (often spheres, axis-aligned bounding boxes or oriented bounding boxes).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] At the bottom of the hierarchy, the size of the volume is just large enough to encompass a single object tightly (or possibly even some smaller fraction of an object in high resolution BVHs).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] As one ascends the hierarchy, each node has its own volume that tightly encompasses all the volumes beneath it.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] At the root of the tree is a volume that encompasses all the volumes in the tree (the whole scene).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] BVHs are useful for speeding up collision detection between objects.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] If an object's bounding volume does not intersect a volume higher in the tree, it cannot intersect any object below that node (so they are all rejected very quickly).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] There are some similarities between BVHs and scene graphs.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A scene graph can easily be adapted to include/become a BVH – if each node has a volume associated or there is a purpose-built "bound node" added in at convenient location in the hierarchy.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This may not be the typical view of a scene graph, but there are benefits to including a BVH in a scene graph.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] An effective way of combining spatial partitioning and scene graphs is by creating a scene leaf node that contains the spatial partitioning data.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This can increase computational efficiency of rendering.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Spatial data is usually static and generally contains non-moving scene data in some partitioned form.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Some systems may have the systems and their rendering separately.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] This is fine and there are no real advantages to either method.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In particular, it is bad to have the scene graph contained within the spatial partitioning system, as the scene graph is better thought of as the grander system to the spatial partitioning.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Very large drawings, or scene graphs that are generated solely at runtime (as happens in ray tracing rendering programs), require defining of group nodes in a more automated fashion.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A raytracer, for example, will take a scene description of a 3D model and build an internal representation that breaks up its individual parts into bounding boxes (also called bounding slabs).
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] These boxes are grouped hierarchically so that ray intersection tests (as part of visibility determination) can be efficiently computed.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A group box that does not intersect an eye ray, for example, can entirely skip testing any of its members.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] A similar efficiency holds in 2D applications as well.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] If the user has magnified a document so that only part of it is visible on their computer screen, and then scrolls in it, it is useful to use a bounding box (or in this case, a bounding rectangle scheme) to quickly determine which scene graph elements are visible and thus actually need to be drawn.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Depending on the particulars of the application's drawing performance, a large part of the scene graph's design can be impacted by rendering efficiency considerations.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] In 3D video games such as Quake, binary space partitioning (BSP) trees are heavily favored to minimize visibility tests.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] BSP trees, however, take a very long time to compute from design scene graphs, and must be recomputed if the design scene graph changes, so the levels tend to remain static, and dynamic characters aren't generally considered in the spatial partitioning scheme.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Scene graphs for dense regular objects such as heightfields and polygon meshes tend to employ quadtrees and octrees, which are specialized variants of a 3D bounding box hierarchy.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Since a heightfield occupies a box volume itself, recursively subdividing this box into eight subboxes (hence the 'oct' in octree) until individual heightfield elements are reached is efficient and natural.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] PHIGS was the first commercial scene graph specification, and became an ANSI standard in 1988.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Disparate implementations were provided by Unix hardware vendors.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] The HOOPS 3D Graphics System appears to have been the first commercial scene graph library provided by a single software vendor.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] It was designed to run on disparate lower-level 2D and 3D interfaces, with the first major production version (v3.0) completed in 1991.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] Silicon Graphics (SGI) released OpenGL Performer or more commonly called Performer in 1991 which was the primary scenegraph system for most SGI products into the future.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] IRIS Inventor 1.0 (1992) was released by SGI, which was a high level scene graph built on top of Performer.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] It was followed up with Open Inventor in 1994, another iteration of the high level scene graph built on top of newer releases of Performer.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] More 3D scene graph libraries can be found in Category:3D scenegraph APIs.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] X3D is a royalty-free open standards file format and run-time architecture to represent and communicate 3D scenes and objects using XML.
[src:unity-engine/scene-graph] It is an ISO-ratified standard that provides a system for the storage, retrieval and playback of real-time graphics content embedded in applications, all within an open architecture to support a wide array of domains and user scenarios.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The engine can be used to create three-dimensional (3D) and two-dimensional (2D) games, as well as interactive simulations.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The engine has been adopted by industries outside video gaming including film, automotive, architecture, engineering, construction, and the United States Armed Forces.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The Unity game engine was launched in 2005, aiming to "democratize" game development by making it accessible to more developers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] It was shown at Worldwide Developers Conference 2005 by Scott Forstall on Mac OS X.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The next year, Unity was named runner-up in the Best Use of Mac OS X Graphics category in Apple Inc.'s Apple Design Awards.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity was initially released for Mac OS X, later adding support for Microsoft Windows and Web browsers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2.0 launched in 2007 with approximately 50 new features.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The release included an optimized terrain engine for detailed 3D environments, real-time dynamic shadows, directional lights and spotlights, video playback, and other features.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The release also added a version control system to allow developers to collaborate more easily.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] It included a Networking Layer for developers to create multiplayer games based on the User Datagram Protocol, offering Network Address Translation, State Synchronization, and Remote Procedure Calls.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] When Apple launched its App Store in 2008, Unity added support for the iPhone.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2.5, released in March 2009, added editor support for Windows.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 3.0 launched in September 2010 with features expanding the engine's graphics features for desktop computers and video game consoles.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In addition to Android support, Unity 3 featured integration of Illuminate Labs' Beast Lightmap tool, deferred rendering, a built-in tree editor, native font rendering, automatic UV mapping, and audio filters, among other features.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In 2012, *VentureBeat* wrote, "Few companies have contributed as much to the flowing of independently produced games as Unity Technologies. [...] More than 1.3 million developers are using its tools to create gee-whiz graphics in their iOS, Android, console, PC, and web-based games.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity wants to be the engine for multi-platform games, period." A May 2012 survey by *Game Developer* magazine indicated Unity as its top game engine for mobile platforms.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In November 2012, Unity Technologies delivered Unity 4.0.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] This version added DirectX 11 and Adobe Flash support, new animation tools called Mecanim, and access to the Linux preview.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Facebook integrated a software development kit for games using the Unity game engine in 2013.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] This featured tools that allowed tracking advertising campaigns and deep linking, where users were directly linked from social media posts to specific portions within games, and easy in-game-image sharing.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In 2016, Facebook developed a new PC gaming platform with Unity.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity provided support for Facebook's gaming platforms, and Unity developers could more quickly export and publish games to Facebook.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] However, some gamers criticized Unity's accessibility due to the high volume of quickly produced games published on the Steam distribution platform by inexperienced developers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Former CEO John Riccitiello said in an interview that he believes this to be a side-effect of Unity's success in democratizing game development: "If I had my way, I'd like to see 50 million people using Unity – although I don't think we're going to get there any time soon.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] I'd like to see high school and college kids using it, people outside the core industry.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] I think it's sad that most people are consumers of technology and not creators.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In December 2016, Unity Technologies announced that they would change the version numbering system for Unity from sequence-based identifiers to year of release to align the versioning with their more frequent release cadence; Unity 5.6 was therefore followed by Unity 2017.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2017 tools featured a real-time graphics rendering engine, color grading and worldbuilding, live operations analytics, and performance reporting.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2017.2 underscored Unity Technologies' plans beyond video games.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] This included new tools such as Timeline, which allowed developers to drag-and-drop animations into games, and Cinemachine, a smart camera system within games.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2017.2 also integrated Autodesk's 3DS Max and Maya tools into the Unity engine for a streamlined asset-sharing in-game iteration process.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2018 featured the Scriptable Render Pipeline for developers to create high-end graphics.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] This included the High-Definition Rendering Pipeline for console and PC experiences, and the Lightweight Rendering Pipeline (later renamed the Universal Render Pipeline) for mobile, virtual reality, and augmented reality.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2018 also included machine learning tools, such as Imitation Learning, whereby games learn from real player habits, support for Magic Leap, and templates for new developers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The C# source code of Unity was published under a "reference-only" license in March 2018, which prohibits reuse and modification.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] As of 2020, software built with Unity's game engine was running on more than 1.5 billion devices.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] According to Unity, apps made with their game engine account for 50 percent of all mobile games and are downloaded more than 3 billion times per month, and approximately 15,000 new projects are started daily with its software.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The *Financial Times* reported that Unity's engine "powers some of the world's most lucrative mobile games", such as *Pokémon Go* and Activision's *Call of Duty Mobile*.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In June 2020, Unity introduced the Mixed and Augmented Reality Studio (MARS), which provides developers with additional functionality for the rules-based generation of augmented reality (AR) applications.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity released Unity Forma, an automotive and retail solution tool, on December 9, 2020.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In June 2020, Unity announced that Unity Editor will support Apple Silicon.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The first beta version shipped later that year.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 2021 brought multiple new features such as Bolt, Unity's Visual Scripting system, a new multiplayer library to support multiplayer games, improved Il2cpp runtime performance, and Volumetric clouds for the High Definition Render pipeline.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Shadow caching and Screen Space Global Illumination for HDRP.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] For the Universal Render Pipeline, it added new features such as point light shadows, Deferred renderer, and general core engine improvements and fixes.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Full Apple Silicon support was also added in Unity 2021.2.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity Hub support for Apple Silicon editors arrived in version 3.0 in January 2022.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Changes to Unity 2022 were intended to improve productivity by reducing the time required to enter play mode and import files and implementing visual search queries and multi-selection in the package manager.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] For 2D projects, changes focused on accelerating core software, import, animation, and physics.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Support for PSD extension files and layer management were added to the 2D PSD Importer, and Delaunay tessellation for 2D physics was added.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] On November 16, 2023, Unity announced that the next version of the engine would be called Unity 6, reverting to the previous version numbering convention.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity 6 launched on October 17, 2024, with new features including new generative AI tools, called Unity Muse and Unity Sentis.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The release introduced new workflows for creating online multiplayer content, performance enhancements for web projects, and improved graphic rendering.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity also announced plans for a revised licensing agreement, including a runtime fee (see § Runtime fee controversy).
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In response to backlash, Unity canceled this runtime fee in September 2024.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity gives users the ability to create games and experiences in both 2D and 3D, and the engine offers a primary scripting API in C# using Mono, for both the Unity editor in the form of plugins, and games themselves, as well as drag and drop functionality.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Within 2D games, Unity allows importation of sprites and an advanced 2D world renderer.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Two separate render pipelines are available, *High Definition Render Pipeline* (HDRP) and *Universal Render Pipeline* (URP, previously LWRP), in addition to the legacy built-in pipeline.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] All three render pipelines are incompatible with each other.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity offers a tool to upgrade shaders using the legacy renderer to URP or HDRP.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Creators can develop and sell user-generated assets to other game makers via the Unity Asset Store.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] This includes 3D and 2D assets and environments for developers to buy and sell.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] By 2018, there had been approximately 40 million downloads through the digital store.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The Unity editor is supported on Windows, macOS, and the Linux platform, while the engine itself currently supports building games for more than 19 different platforms, including mobile, desktop, consoles, and virtual-reality platforms.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Formerly supported platforms are Wii, Wii U, Oculus, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, Tizen, PlayStation Vita, 3DS, BlackBerry 10, Windows Phone 8, Samsung Smart TV, Gear VR, Daydream, Vuforia, Facebook Gameroom, and Stadia.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity formerly supported other platforms including its own Unity Web Player, a Web browser plugin.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] However, it was deprecated in favor of WebGL.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Since version 5, Unity has been offering its WebGL bundle compiled to JavaScript using a 2-stage language translator (C# to C++ and finally to JavaScript).
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity was the default software development kit (SDK) used for Nintendo's Wii U video game console, with a free copy included by Nintendo with each Wii U developer license.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity Technologies called this bundling of a third-party SDK an "industry first".
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In August 2023, Unity China announced that it would soon launch a Chinese edition called **Tuanjie Engine** (Chinese: 团结引擎; pinyin: *Tuánjié Yǐnqíng*) based on Unity 2022 LTS, which includes support for Chinese platforms like Weixin Mini Game, OpenHarmony and AliOS.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] During its first ten years as a product, the paid versions of Unity were sold outright; in 2016, the corporation changed to a subscription model.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity has free and paid licensing options.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The free license is for personal use or smaller companies generating less than $100,000 annually, later raised to $200,000, and the subscriptions are based on revenues generated by the games using Unity.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The subscription-based versions also include additional features geared towards professional projects, including analytics, performance analysis and error reporting, and Cloud Build among others.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The paid option, Unity Pro, had been required for developers that had over $200,000 in annual revenue, but this also could have been provided for console developers through a Preferred Platform License from the console manufacturer.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The Unity Pro keys would have been part of the other SDK from the console manufacturer that the developer paid for.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In May 2016, Unity released "Unity Plus", a mid-range tier between Personal and Pro that provides tools and benefits oriented towards "first-time commercial developers".
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In June 2021, Unity changed its licensing terms to require any developer making games on the closed console systems (PlayStation, Nintendo Switch, and Xbox) regardless of revenue to have a Unity Pro license or a Preferred Platform License Key from the manufacturers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Sony and Nintendo provide this as part of the SDK, but Microsoft had yet to implement this functionality for their SDK.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The engine source code is licensed on a "per-case basis via special arrangements".
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] On September 12, 2023, Unity announced that use of the engine would become subject to royalties (referred to as a "runtime fee") beginning in January 2024, calculated per-installation and charged monthly, if the product reaches specific revenue and lifetime installation thresholds.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The new terms faced criticism from game developers who had been using Unity for years, particularly regarding how this fee would be calculated and enforced, and the implications for demos, freemium games and bundles distributed for charitable causes.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity then issued a statement clarifying the definition of a chargeable "installation", and announced that the fee would not apply to charity games or bundles.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Many indie developers, including *Among Us* developer Innersloth and *Slay the Spire* developer Mega Crit, announced that they would switch to other engines for future games, specifically the Godot engine for *Slay the Spire 2*.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] An analysis by *Ars Technica* found that several older versions of Unity's terms of service would allow developers to continue to release their software without having to pay the new fee, as long as they did not update their project after the January 1, 2024 date.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] *Ars Technica* also discovered that Unity had apparently removed a GitHub repository that permitted developers to track changes in Unity's terms of service; Mega Crit accused Unity of having done so to apply their new financial model to games retroactively.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] An analysis by *Game Developer* came to the conclusion that the changes were intended to encourage games with large install bases such as *Genshin Impact*, *Subway Surfers* and *Hearthstone* to migrate to Unity services in order to get a fee reduction.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In response to this negative feedback, Unity Technologies introduced revised runtime fee terms on September 22, 2023.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity Technologies faced a 60% decline in stock price over the year to May 2024, partially attributed to the runtime fee policy.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Usage of Unity waned after these licensing decisions within the indie game community.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The use of Unity at the 2023 Global Game Jam was 61%; this declined to 36% for 2024.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] A similar decline was recorded by the GMTK Game Jam.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] CEO Matthew Bromberg announced in September 2024 that the company was discontinuing the runtime fee model of licensing, and instead would annually increase the price of existing plans.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] CVE-2025-59489, an arbitrary code execution vulnerability was discovered in June 2025, for games on Android, Windows, MacOS, and Linux, built with all Unity versions from 2017 onward.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Due to errors with command line argument processing, applications developed using Unity could be made to load arbitrary libraries and execute code with access to all data from the application at the same privilege level.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity patched the vulnerability on October 2, 2025 before notifying the public on the next day.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] It was rated as 8.4 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System, though Unity reported they were unaware of anyone that has used the exploit.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Multiple developers rushed out patches for their games affected by the exploit, while Microsoft delisted several of its games from storefronts, including *Fallout Shelter* and *Pentiment*, until they were able to supply the necessary patches.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] A patching tool was also released to allow for users to patch applications manually.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The engine is used in games including *Pokémon Go*, *Monument Valley*, *Call of Duty: Mobile*, *Beat Saber* and *Cuphead* according to the *Financial Times* in 2020.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Some early commercial games in 2007 included *Splume* (Flashbang Studios), *Magical Flying Pink Pony Game* (Starscene Software) and *Global Conflicts: Palestine* (Serious Games Interactive).
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity technology is the basis for most virtual reality and augmented reality experiences, and *Fortune* said Unity "dominates the virtual reality business".
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity allows researchers in the field of deep reinforcement learning to train agents inside Unity-created environments.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity Machine Learning Agents can act as virtual characters or robots to learn creative strategies to interact with simulated real-world environments.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The software is used, for example, to develop robots and self-driving cars.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In the 2010s, Unity Technologies used its game engine to transition into other industries using the real-time 3D platform, including film and automotive.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity first experimented in filmmaking with *Adam*, a short film about a robot escaping from prison.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Later, Unity partnered with filmmaker Neill Blomkamp, whose Oats Studios used the engine's tools, including real-time rendering and Cinemachine, to create two computer-generated short films, *Adam: The Mirror* and *Adam: The Prophet*.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] At the 2017 Unite Europe conference in Amsterdam, Unity focused on filmmaking with Unity 2017.1's new Cinemachine tool.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] In 2018, Disney Television Animation launched three shorts, called Baymax Dreams, that were created using the Unity engine.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The Unity engine was also used by Disney to create backgrounds for the 2019 film *The Lion King*.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Automakers use Unity's technology to create full-scale models of new vehicles in virtual reality, build virtual assembly lines, and train workers.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity is also developing solutions in the fields of architecture, engineering, and construction.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Unity's engine is used by DeepMind, an Alphabet company, to train artificial intelligence.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] Other uses being pursued by Unity Technologies include architecture, engineering, and construction.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] On December 16, 2013, Unity Technologies Japan revealed an official mascot character named Unity-chan (ユニティちゃん, *Yuniti-chan*), real name Kohaku Ōtori (大鳥 こはく, *Ōtori Kohaku*) (voiced by Asuka Kakumoto).
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The character's associated game data was released in early 2014.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The character was designed by Unity Technologies Japan designer "ntny" as an open-source heroine character.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] The company allows the use of Unity-chan and related characters in secondary projects under certain licenses.
[src:unity-engine/unity-game-engine] For example, Unity-chan appears as a playable character in *Runbow*.
